(*   SECTION 1: WHAT IS AN EARTHQUAKE?                          *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ============================================================ *)
(* ============================================================ *)

(* ---- 1.1 Earth's interior structure ----                      *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The Earth is a differentiated body with a layered internal    *)
(* structure, shaped by 4.5 billion years of gravitational       *)
(* separation and radiogenic heating. At the centre lies the     *)
(* inner core, a solid sphere of iron-nickel alloy with a        *)
(* radius of approximately 1221 km. Temperatures there reach     *)
(* ~5200 K, but the immense pressure (over 330 GPa) keeps the   *)
(* iron crystalline. Surrounding it is the outer core, a         *)
(* convecting shell of liquid iron extending to a radius of      *)
(* 3480 km from the centre. This liquid layer is the source of   *)
(* Earth's magnetic field via the geodynamo. Above the core      *)
(* lies the mantle, composed primarily of silicate minerals       *)
(* (olivine, pyroxene, perovskite at depth), extending to a      *)
(* mean radius of 6371 km. The mantle is solid on seismic time   *)
(* scales but flows viscously over geological time, driving the  *)
(* convection currents that move tectonic plates. Finally, the   *)
(* crust is a thin veneer --- just 5-7 km thick beneath the     *)
(* oceans (basaltic) and 30-70 km thick beneath the continents   *)
(* (granitic). It is within and just below this crust that most  *)
(* earthquakes originate.                                        *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 1.2 Plate tectonics and strain accumulation ----         *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Earth's surface is divided into approximately 15 major        *)
(* lithospheric plates and numerous smaller ones. These rigid     *)
(* plates --- comprising the crust and the uppermost mantle      *)
(* (the lithosphere) --- float atop the partially molten         *)
(* asthenosphere. Driven by mantle convection, slab pull at      *)
(* subduction zones, and ridge push at mid-ocean ridges, the     *)
(* plates move at rates of 2 to 10 cm per year. While this may   *)
(* seem negligible, over decades to centuries the cumulative     *)
(* displacement across plate boundaries amounts to metres of     *)
(* strain stored as elastic deformation in the surrounding rock. *)
(*                                                              *)
(* At convergent boundaries (subduction zones and continental    *)
(* collision zones), plates are thrust together --- producing    *)
(* the world's largest earthquakes (e.g. M9.5 Chile 1960,       *)
(* M9.1 Tohoku 2011). At transform boundaries (e.g. the San     *)
(* Andreas Fault), plates slide past one another. At divergent   *)
(* boundaries (mid-ocean ridges), plates pull apart. Each        *)
(* boundary type produces characteristic seismicity patterns     *)
(* and focal mechanisms.                                         *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 1.3 Elastic rebound theory ----                          *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The physical mechanism of earthquakes was first clearly       *)
(* articulated by H. F. Reid in 1910, following his study of    *)
(* the 1906 San Francisco earthquake on the San Andreas Fault.  *)
(* Reid's "elastic rebound theory" states: rock on either side   *)
(* of a locked fault deforms elastically under tectonic stress   *)
(* until the accumulated shear stress exceeds the frictional     *)
(* strength of the fault surface. At that point, the fault       *)
(* ruptures suddenly, and the rock on each side snaps back       *)
(* ("rebounds") to an undeformed state. The elastic strain       *)
(* energy stored over decades is released in seconds as seismic  *)
(* waves that radiate outward from the rupture zone.             *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 1.4 Quantifying earthquakes ----                         *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The size of an earthquake is quantified by the seismic        *)
(* moment, a physical measure of the total deformation:          *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   Seismic Moment:                                             *)
(*     M0 = mu * A * d                                           *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   where:                                                      *)
(*     mu = shear modulus of the rock [Pa]                       *)
(*          (typically ~30 GPa for crustal rock,                 *)
(*           ~70 GPa for upper mantle)                           *)
(*     A  = area of the fault rupture surface [m^2]              *)
(*     d  = average displacement (slip) across the fault [m]     *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   Moment Magnitude (Kanamori 1977):                           *)
(*     Mw = (2/3)(Log10[M0] - 9.1)     [M0 in N*m]              *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   Energy-Magnitude Relation (Gutenberg & Richter 1956,        *)
(*   refined by Kanamori 1977):                                  *)
(*     Log10[Es] = 1.5 Mw + 4.8        [Es in Joules]           *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The moment magnitude scale is logarithmic: each unit increase *)
(* in Mw corresponds to a factor of 10^1.5 ~ 31.6 increase in  *)
(* radiated seismic energy. Some representative fault dimensions:*)
(*                                                              *)
(*   M6: fault area ~ 20 km x 10 km, slip ~ 0.5 m               *)
(*       (e.g. a moderate damaging earthquake)                   *)
(*   M7: fault area ~ 70 km x 25 km, slip ~ 1 m                 *)
(*       (e.g. 2023 Turkey Mw 7.8)                               *)
(*   M9: fault area ~ 1000 km x 200 km, slip ~ 10 m             *)
(*       (e.g. 2011 Tohoku, 2004 Sumatra)                        *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 1.5 Focal mechanisms ----                                *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The geometry of fault rupture creates a characteristic        *)
(* radiation pattern known as a double-couple source. The first  *)
(* motion of P-waves divides the focal sphere into four          *)
(* quadrants: two compressional (first motion away from the      *)
(* source) and two dilatational (first motion toward the         *)
(* source). When projected onto the lower hemisphere, this       *)
(* produces the familiar "beach ball" diagram used in            *)
(* seismology. The pattern of the beach ball reveals the fault   *)
(* orientation and slip direction.                               *)
(*                                                              *)
(* This double-couple radiation pattern is fundamentally         *)
(* different from an explosion, which radiates energy            *)
(* isotropically (equally in all directions). This difference    *)
(* is the physical basis for discriminating earthquakes from     *)
(* nuclear tests --- a topic we shall return to in Section 9.   *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 1.6 Our earthquake catalog ----                          *)
(*                                                              *)
(* We have assembled a catalog of significant earthquakes        *)
(* spanning the magnitude range M6.0 to M9.5, including         *)
(* the most destructive events in recorded history as well as    *)
(* several nuclear tests for comparison. Let us begin by         *)
(* displaying this catalog and plotting the events on a globe.   *)

(* Display the full earthquake catalog as a formatted table *)
displayCatalog[]

(* Plot all catalog events on an orthographic globe projection *)
plotEventMap[]


