(*   SECTION 2: THE PHYSICS OF SEISMIC WAVES                    *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ============================================================ *)
(* ============================================================ *)

(* ---- 2.1 The equation of motion for a continuum ----          *)
(*                                                              *)
(* We begin from first principles. Consider a small volume       *)
(* element of rock within the Earth. Newton's second law for a   *)
(* continuous elastic medium takes the form:                      *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   rho * D^2 u / Dt^2 = Div[sigma] + f                        *)
(*                                                              *)
(* where:                                                        *)
(*   rho     = mass density [kg/m^3]                             *)
(*   u       = displacement vector field [m]                     *)
(*   sigma   = Cauchy stress tensor [Pa]                         *)
(*   f       = body force density (e.g. gravity) [N/m^3]         *)
(*                                                              *)
(* For seismic wave propagation, we neglect body forces (they    *)
(* produce only static deformation) and focus on the dynamic     *)
(* perturbation about the equilibrium state.                     *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 2.2 Hooke's law for isotropic elastic media ----         *)
(*                                                              *)
(* For a linear, isotropic elastic solid, the stress-strain      *)
(* relation (generalized Hooke's law) is:                        *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   sigma_ij = lambda * delta_ij * epsilon_kk + 2 mu * eps_ij  *)
(*                                                              *)
(* where:                                                        *)
(*   lambda, mu = Lame parameters [Pa]                           *)
(*   delta_ij   = Kronecker delta                                *)
(*   epsilon_ij = (1/2)(du_i/dx_j + du_j/dx_i)  (strain tensor) *)
(*   epsilon_kk = Div[u]  (volumetric strain / dilatation)       *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The Lame parameter mu is the shear modulus (rigidity), and    *)
(* lambda is related to the bulk modulus K by:                   *)
(*   K = lambda + (2/3) mu                                       *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 2.3 The Navier-Cauchy equation ----                      *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Substituting Hooke's law into the equation of motion and      *)
(* using the strain-displacement relation yields the             *)
(* Navier-Cauchy equation for elastic wave propagation:          *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   rho * D^2 u / Dt^2 = (lambda + 2 mu) Grad[Div[u]]         *)
(*                         - mu Curl[Curl[u]]                    *)
(*                                                              *)
(* or equivalently, using the vector identity                    *)
(*   Curl[Curl[u]] = Grad[Div[u]] - Laplacian[u]:               *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   rho * D^2 u / Dt^2 = (lambda + mu) Grad[Div[u]]            *)
(*                         + mu Laplacian[u]                     *)
(*                                                              *)
(* This is a coupled system of PDEs for the three components     *)
(* of displacement. The key insight of seismology is that it     *)
(* can be decoupled using the Helmholtz decomposition.           *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 2.4 Helmholtz decomposition: P- and S-waves ----         *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Any vector field can be decomposed into irrotational and      *)
(* solenoidal parts:                                             *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   u = Grad[phi] + Curl[psi]                                   *)
(*                                                              *)
(* where phi is a scalar potential and psi is a vector           *)
(* potential. Substituting into the Navier-Cauchy equation and   *)
(* separating:                                                   *)
(*                                                              *)
(* P-waves (from phi, the compressional potential):               *)
(*   Laplacian[phi] = (1/alpha^2) * D^2 phi / Dt^2              *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   where alpha = Sqrt[(lambda + 2 mu) / rho]                   *)
(*                                                              *)
(* S-waves (from psi, the shear potential):                       *)
(*   Laplacian[psi] = (1/beta^2) * D^2 psi / Dt^2               *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   where beta = Sqrt[mu / rho]                                 *)
(*                                                              *)
(* These are classical wave equations. The solutions propagate   *)
(* at velocities alpha (P-wave) and beta (S-wave) respectively. *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 2.5 P-wave properties ----                               *)
(*                                                              *)
(* P-waves (primary waves) are compressional: the particle       *)
(* motion is parallel (longitudinal) to the direction of wave    *)
(* propagation. They are the fastest seismic waves and           *)
(* therefore arrive first at any seismometer. Typical values:    *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   In the crust:      alpha ~ 6.0 km/s                        *)
(*   In the upper mantle: alpha ~ 8.0 km/s                      *)
(*   At the core-mantle boundary: alpha ~ 13.7 km/s             *)
(*   In the outer core (liquid): alpha ~ 8.0-10.3 km/s          *)
(*   In the inner core: alpha ~ 11.0-11.3 km/s                  *)
(*                                                              *)
(* P-waves can propagate through both solids and liquids,        *)
(* because compression does not require shear rigidity.          *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 2.6 S-wave properties ----                               *)
(*                                                              *)
(* S-waves (secondary waves) are shear waves: the particle       *)
(* motion is perpendicular (transverse) to the direction of      *)
(* propagation. They are slower than P-waves by a factor that    *)
(* depends on Poisson's ratio:                                   *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   alpha / beta = Sqrt[(lambda + 2 mu) / mu]                   *)
(*                = Sqrt[2(1 - nu) / (1 - 2 nu)]                *)
(*                                                              *)
(* For a Poisson ratio of nu = 0.25 (a common approximation     *)
(* for crustal rock), this gives alpha/beta = Sqrt[3] ~ 1.73.   *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Crucially, S-waves CANNOT propagate in fluids, because the   *)
(* shear modulus mu = 0 in a liquid. This has a profound         *)
(* consequence: S-waves are blocked by the liquid outer core,    *)
(* creating a "shadow zone" for direct S-wave arrivals at        *)
(* epicentral distances between about 104 and 140 degrees.       *)
(* This shadow zone was one of the key pieces of evidence        *)
(* proving the existence of a liquid outer core (Oldham 1906,    *)
(* Gutenberg 1913).                                              *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 2.7 Surface waves ----                                   *)
(*                                                              *)
(* In addition to body waves (P and S), the free surface of      *)
(* the Earth supports surface waves, which are confined to the   *)
(* near-surface region and decay exponentially with depth.       *)
(* There are two types:                                          *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Rayleigh waves (Lord Rayleigh 1885):                          *)
(*   - Retrograde elliptical particle motion in the vertical     *)
(*     plane containing the propagation direction                *)
(*   - Velocity ~ 0.92 beta for a Poisson solid                 *)
(*   - Amplitude decays exponentially with depth, with           *)
(*     significant motion down to about one wavelength           *)
(*   - Exist on any free surface of an elastic half-space        *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Love waves (A. E. H. Love 1911):                              *)
(*   - Transverse horizontal particle motion (SH polarization)  *)
(*   - Require a low-velocity layer over a half-space            *)
(*   - Slightly faster than Rayleigh waves                      *)
(*   - Dispersive: velocity depends on frequency                 *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Surface waves are critically important because:               *)
(*   - Their amplitude decays as 1/Sqrt[r] (geometric spreading *)
(*     on a 2D surface), compared to 1/r for body waves          *)
(*     spreading on a 3D wavefront. This means surface waves    *)
(*     dominate far-field seismograms.                           *)
(*   - They carry most of the energy in large earthquakes        *)
(*   - They cause the majority of earthquake damage              *)
(*   - On a sphere, the geometric spreading factor becomes      *)
(*     1/Sqrt[Sin[Delta]], where Delta is the epicentral         *)
(*     distance in radians. This produces a focusing effect      *)
(*     at the antipodal point (Delta = Pi), where Sin[Delta]    *)
(*     approaches zero and amplitudes are amplified.             *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 2.8 Attenuation ----                                     *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Real seismic waves lose energy as they propagate, due to      *)
(* anelastic absorption (conversion of mechanical energy to      *)
(* heat through internal friction in the rock). This is          *)
(* quantified by the quality factor Q:                           *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   Amplitude ~ Exp[-Pi f t / Q]                                *)
(*                                                              *)
(* where f is frequency and t is travel time. Typical values:    *)
(*   Q_P ~ 300-500 in the mantle                                *)
(*   Q_S ~ 100-200 in the mantle (shear attenuation is higher)  *)
(*   Q ~ 5000+ in the inner core                                *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Low Q means high attenuation. The asthenosphere (the          *)
(* partially molten zone beneath the lithosphere, 80-220 km     *)
(* depth) has particularly low Q values, which is evidence       *)
(* for partial melting there.                                    *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Note: In our PREM-based simulations below, we compute         *)
(* travel times using the velocity model but do not explicitly   *)
(* model attenuation. The synthetic seismograms use Ricker       *)
(* wavelets whose amplitude is determined by the per-station     *)
(* normalization scheme rather than by physical attenuation      *)
(* --- this is a common simplification in Ground Motion          *)
(* Visualizations.                                               *)


