(*   SECTION 4: RAY THEORY AND TRAVEL TIMES                     *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ============================================================ *)
(* ============================================================ *)

(* ---- 4.1 Snell's law in a spherically symmetric Earth ----    *)
(*                                                              *)
(* In a medium where the velocity varies continuously with       *)
(* depth, seismic waves do not travel in straight lines ---      *)
(* they are refracted. In a spherically symmetric Earth (such    *)
(* as PREM), Snell's law takes the form:                         *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   p = r Sin[i] / v(r) = constant along a ray                 *)
(*                                                              *)
(* where:                                                        *)
(*   p    = ray parameter [s/rad] (conserved quantity)           *)
(*   r    = radial distance from Earth's center [km]             *)
(*   i    = angle of incidence (angle between ray and radial     *)
(*          direction) [rad]                                      *)
(*   v(r) = seismic velocity at radius r [km/s]                  *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The ray parameter p is the seismological analogue of          *)
(* Snell's law in optics. It is conserved along each ray path   *)
(* and uniquely determines the ray geometry.                     *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 4.2 The turning point ----                               *)
(*                                                              *)
(* A ray traveling downward into the Earth encounters increasing *)
(* velocity (in general), which bends the ray back toward the   *)
(* surface. The turning point occurs where the ray becomes       *)
(* horizontal (i = Pi/2), which gives:                           *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   p = r_tp / v(r_tp)                                          *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Defining the slowness function eta(r) = r / v(r), the        *)
(* turning point radius r_tp is the solution of:                 *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   eta(r_tp) = p                                               *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Rays with smaller p (steeper take-off angle) penetrate        *)
(* deeper and emerge at greater epicentral distances.            *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 4.3 Travel time and distance integrals ----              *)
(*                                                              *)
(* For a ray with parameter p traveling from the surface to its  *)
(* turning point and back, the epicentral distance Delta and     *)
(* travel time T are given by the integrals:                     *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   Delta(p) = 2 Integrate[p / (r Sqrt[eta(r)^2 - p^2]),       *)
(*                          {r, r_tp, R}]                        *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   T(p) = 2 Integrate[eta(r)^2 / (r Sqrt[eta(r)^2 - p^2]),   *)
(*                      {r, r_tp, R}]                            *)
(*                                                              *)
(* where R = 6371 km is Earth's radius. These are evaluated      *)
(* numerically using the PREM velocity profile.                  *)
(*                                                              *)
(* A crucial point: these integrals depend ONLY on the velocity  *)
(* model and the ray parameter p --- they are independent of     *)
(* the earthquake magnitude. A M9 megathrust and a M2            *)
(* microearthquake at the same location produce P-waves that     *)
(* arrive at any given station at exactly the same time. The     *)
(* magnitude affects the amplitude and duration of the signal,   *)
(* not the travel time. This universality is what makes          *)
(* seismic travel time tables possible.                          *)

(* Plot travel time curves for P, S, and Rayleigh waves *)
(* as functions of epicentral distance in degrees *)
plotTravelTimeCurves[]

(* Plot ray paths through the Earth's interior, showing how *)
(* rays at different take-off angles sample different depths *)
plotRayPaths[]


