(* ---- 5.1 The energy-magnitude relation ----                   *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The total seismic energy radiated by an earthquake is         *)
(* related to its moment magnitude by the Gutenberg-Richter-     *)
(* Kanamori relation:                                            *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   Log10[Es] = 1.5 Mw + 4.8        [Es in Joules]             *)
(*                                                              *)
(* This relation reveals the extraordinary range of seismic      *)
(* energy: each unit increase in magnitude corresponds to a      *)
(* factor of 10^1.5 ~ 31.6 increase in energy. Going from       *)
(* M6 to M9 (three magnitude units) means an energy increase    *)
(* of 31.6^3 ~ 31,623 --- over four orders of magnitude.        *)
(*                                                              *)
(* To put these numbers in perspective:                          *)
(*   M6.0:  Es ~ 6.3 x 10^13 J  ~ 15 kilotons TNT              *)
(*   M7.0:  Es ~ 2.0 x 10^15 J  ~ 474 kilotons TNT             *)
(*   M8.0:  Es ~ 6.3 x 10^16 J  ~ 15 megatons TNT              *)
(*   M9.0:  Es ~ 2.0 x 10^18 J  ~ 474 megatons TNT             *)
(*   M9.5:  Es ~ 1.1 x 10^19 J  ~ 2700 megatons TNT            *)
(*          (Chile 1960 --- largest recorded earthquake)         *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The 1960 Chile earthquake released energy equivalent to       *)
(* roughly 2700 megatons of TNT --- about 54,000 times the      *)
(* yield of the Hiroshima bomb (20 kt) and far exceeding the    *)
(* largest nuclear weapon ever detonated (Tsar Bomba, 50 Mt).   *)

(* Display a formatted comparison table of earthquake energies *)
(* alongside nuclear test yields and everyday energy scales *)
displayEnergyComparison[]

(* Plot a bar chart of seismic energy for catalog events *)
(* on a logarithmic scale, color-coded by magnitude *)
