(*   SECTION 7: SUPERSHEAR RUPTURE                              *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ============================================================ *)
(* ============================================================ *)

(* ---- 7.1 Sub-Rayleigh and supershear rupture ----             *)
(*                                                              *)
(* In most earthquakes, the rupture front propagates along the   *)
(* fault at a velocity below the Rayleigh wave speed --- this    *)
(* is called sub-Rayleigh rupture, and typical rupture speeds    *)
(* are 70-90% of the local S-wave velocity, roughly 2.5-3.2     *)
(* km/s in the crust.                                            *)
(*                                                              *)
(* However, theory predicts (Andrews 1976, Burridge 1973) that   *)
(* under certain conditions --- particularly on smooth,          *)
(* straight fault segments with sufficient pre-stress --- the    *)
(* rupture can accelerate through the "forbidden zone" between   *)
(* the Rayleigh and S-wave speeds and enter the supershear      *)
(* regime, where the rupture speed exceeds the S-wave velocity.  *)
(* This has been confirmed observationally in several events:    *)
(*   - 1999 Izmit, Turkey (Mw 7.4)                              *)
(*   - 2001 Kunlun, Tibet (Mw 7.8)                              *)
(*   - 2018 Palu, Indonesia (Mw 7.5)                             *)
(*   - 2025 Myanmar (Mw 7.7)                                    *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 7.2 The Mach cone ----                                   *)
(*                                                              *)
(* When the rupture speed v_rupture exceeds the S-wave speed     *)
(* v_S, the radiated S-waves cannot outrun the rupture front.   *)
(* They pile up along a conical wavefront --- a Mach cone ---    *)
(* exactly analogous to the sonic boom produced by a supersonic  *)
(* aircraft. The half-angle of the Mach cone is:                 *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   Sin[theta_Mach] = v_S / v_rupture                           *)
(*                                                              *)
(* For the 2025 Myanmar earthquake, preliminary analyses         *)
(* suggest a rupture velocity of approximately 5.5 km/s, while  *)
(* the local crustal S-wave speed is about 3.5 km/s. This       *)
(* gives a Mach number of 5.5/3.5 ~ 1.57 and a Mach cone       *)
(* half-angle of about 39.5 degrees.                             *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The practical consequence of supershear rupture is that the   *)
(* Mach cone concentrates seismic energy along a narrow beam,   *)
(* producing unusually intense shaking at locations that lie     *)
(* in its path --- analogous to the focused shock of a sonic     *)
(* boom. This can lead to unexpectedly severe damage at          *)
(* locations far from the epicenter.                             *)

