(*   SECTION 8: NUCLEAR TESTS AS SEISMIC SOURCES                *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ============================================================ *)
(* ============================================================ *)

(* ---- 8.1 The Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty ----       *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty (CTBT), opened     *)
(* for signature in 1996, bans all nuclear explosions. Its       *)
(* verification regime relies heavily on seismology: the         *)
(* International Monitoring System (IMS) operates a global       *)
(* network of seismic stations specifically designed to detect   *)
(* and identify clandestine nuclear tests.                       *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Underground nuclear explosions are efficient seismic sources  *)
(* --- even a 1-kiloton device produces a seismic signal         *)
(* equivalent to roughly a M4 earthquake, easily detectable      *)
(* at teleseismic distances by the IMS network.                  *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 8.2 Yield-magnitude scaling ----                         *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The relationship between nuclear yield (Y, in kilotons) and   *)
(* body-wave magnitude (mb) is approximately:                    *)
(*                                                              *)
(*   mb = a + b * Log10[Y]                                       *)
(*                                                              *)
(* with typical values a ~ 4.0, b ~ 0.75 for well-coupled       *)
(* underground explosions. This means:                           *)
(*   1 kt  -> mb ~ 4.0                                          *)
(*   10 kt -> mb ~ 4.75                                          *)
(*   100 kt -> mb ~ 5.5                                          *)
(*   1 Mt  -> mb ~ 6.25                                          *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Cavity decoupling can reduce the observed magnitude by up     *)
(* to ~1.5 units, making small tests harder to detect --- but    *)
(* requires impractically large cavities for yields above a      *)
(* few kilotons.                                                 *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 8.3 Source physics differences ----                      *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The fundamental difference between an earthquake and a        *)
(* nuclear explosion as seismic sources lies in their source     *)
(* mechanism:                                                    *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Earthquake (double-couple / deviatoric source):               *)
(*   - Shear dislocation on a fault plane                        *)
(*   - Radiation pattern has four lobes (two compressional,      *)
(*     two dilatational)                                         *)
(*   - Efficient generation of S-waves and surface waves        *)
(*   - Surface wave magnitude Ms is large relative to mb        *)
(*                                                              *)
(* Nuclear explosion (isotropic source):                          *)
(*   - Sudden expansion of a cavity (point source of pressure)   *)
(*   - Radiation pattern is spherically symmetric --- all        *)
(*     first motions are compressional                           *)
(*   - Very weak S-wave generation (only from interaction with   *)
(*     the free surface and pre-existing structure)              *)
(*   - Surface wave magnitude Ms is small relative to mb        *)

(* Plot the yield-mb scaling relation for underground nuclear tests *)
plotYieldMbRelation[]

(* Display the North Korean nuclear test series with estimated *)
(* yields and observed magnitudes *)
displayNKTestSeries[]

(* Side-by-side wavefront snapshots comparing earthquake vs *)
(* nuclear test radiation patterns *)
plotEarthquakeVsNuclearSnapshots[]


