(*                                                              *)
(*   SECTION 9: EARTHQUAKE vs EXPLOSION DISCRIMINATION          *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ============================================================ *)
(* ============================================================ *)

(* ---- 9.1 The mb-Ms discrimination method ----                 *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The most widely used seismic discriminant between             *)
(* earthquakes and explosions is the mb:Ms criterion. Body-wave  *)
(* magnitude (mb) is measured from short-period P-waves          *)
(* (typically ~1 Hz), while surface-wave magnitude (Ms) is       *)
(* measured from long-period Rayleigh waves (~20 s period).      *)
(*                                                              *)
(* For earthquakes, the efficient generation of surface waves    *)
(* means that Ms is large relative to mb. Empirically:           *)
(*   Earthquakes: Ms ~ 1.15 mb - 0.52  (Marshall & Basham 1972) *)
(*                                                              *)
(* For explosions, the weak surface wave generation means that   *)
(* Ms is systematically lower for the same mb. This creates a   *)
(* clear separation in the mb-Ms plot: earthquakes cluster       *)
(* above the discrimination line, explosions below.              *)
(*                                                              *)
(* ---- 9.2 Why the method works ----                            *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The physical basis is the source mechanism difference:        *)
(*   - Earthquakes (double-couple) efficiently excite Rayleigh   *)
(*     waves because the shear dislocation has a strong          *)
(*     vertical force component                                  *)
(*   - Explosions (isotropic) generate Rayleigh waves only       *)
(*     through secondary mechanisms (spall, tectonic release)    *)
(*     that are much weaker                                      *)
(*                                                              *)
(* The mb:Ms criterion has been successfully applied to          *)
(* identify all confirmed nuclear tests since the 1960s and     *)
(* is a cornerstone of CTBT verification. It was instrumental   *)
(* in confirming the North Korean tests (2006-2017).             *)

(* Plot the mb-Ms discrimination diagram showing clear *)
(* separation between earthquakes and nuclear tests *)
plotMbMsDiscrimination[]

(* Show the contrasting source mechanisms: double-couple *)
(* (earthquake) vs isotropic (explosion) radiation patterns *)
plotSourceMechanisms[]


